# Onshape authentication

Every Onshape REST call (`https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10/…`) must carry credentials.
Three schemes, in order of production-fitness: **HMAC-SHA256 request signing** (the
production default for a single account), **HTTP Basic** (`access:secret`, local
testing only), and **OAuth2** (authorization-code grant, for apps acting on *other*
users' accounts). Keys come from the dev portal — the **secret is shown once**.

## Keys

- **API key pair** (`access` + `secret`): create at `dev-portal.onshape.com` →
  *API keys*. Copy the secret immediately; it is never displayed again. Drives both
  HMAC and Basic. Export as `ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY` / `ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY`.
- **OAuth app** (`client_id` + `client_secret`): register at `dev-portal.onshape.com` →
  *OAuth applications*. Same one-time-secret rule. Drives the OAuth2 flow below.

## HMAC-SHA256 request signing (production)

Sign each request individually; the signature covers the method, a per-request
nonce, the date, the content type, and the path+query — so a captured request can't
be replayed or retargeted. The string-to-sign is six fields, **each newline-`\n`-terminated**
(including a trailing `\n` after the query), then the **whole string lowercased**
before HMAC:

```
to_sign = lower(
    method      + "\n" +   # GET, POST, DELETE…
    On-Nonce    + "\n" +   # the same nonce sent in the On-Nonce header
    Date        + "\n" +   # the same value sent in the Date header (RFC 1123)
    Content-Type+ "\n" +   # e.g. application/json
    path        + "\n" +   # URL path only, e.g. /api/v10/users/sessioninfo
    query       + "\n"     # raw query string ("" if none)
)
signature   = base64( HMAC_SHA256(secret_key, to_sign) )
```

Then the request carries:

```
Authorization: On <accessKey>:HmacSHA256:<base64 signature>
Date:          <RFC 1123, e.g. Mon, 28 Jun 2026 12:00:00 GMT>
On-Nonce:      <25-char alphanumeric nonce, unique per request>
Content-Type:  application/json
```

The `Date` and `On-Nonce` values in the headers **must be byte-identical** to the
ones folded into `to_sign`, or the server rejects the signature. The nonce is a
fresh ≥25-char alphanumeric string per call; the date is RFC 1123 in GMT.

The runnable signer lives in `examples/onshape/onshape_edit.py` (`hmac_headers`).
Quoting its core exactly:

```python
nonce = uuid.uuid4().hex + uuid.uuid4().hex[:9]  # >=16 alphanumeric chars
date  = format_datetime(datetime.now(timezone.utc), usegmt=True)
path  = urlparse(url).path
query = urlparse(url).query or ""
to_sign = f"{method}\n{nonce}\n{date}\n{content_type}\n{path}\n{query}\n".lower()
sig = base64.b64encode(
    hmac.new(secret_key.encode(), to_sign.encode(), hashlib.sha256).digest()
).decode()
headers = {
    "Authorization": f"On {access_key}:HmacSHA256:{sig}",
    "Date": date,
    "On-Nonce": nonce,
    "Content-Type": content_type,
    "Accept": "application/json",
}
```

(The `uuid` recipe yields a 41-char hex nonce — comfortably past the 25-char floor;
any unique alphanumeric string of sufficient length works.)

## HTTP Basic (`access:secret`, local/testing only)

Send the API key pair as HTTP Basic credentials over **HTTPS only** — no signing,
no nonce, no date. Trivially simple, so it is the right tool for a quick local probe
or a CI smoke test, and the **wrong** tool for anything long-lived: the secret
travels on every request and there is no replay protection.

```bash
curl -u "$ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY:$ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY" \
  https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10/users/sessioninfo
```

In Python `requests`: `requests.get(url, auth=(access, secret))`.

## OAuth2 (authorization-code grant, distributed apps)

When your app acts on **another user's** documents you can't hold their API keys —
use the OAuth2 authorization-code grant. Register an OAuth application in the dev
portal (set its **redirect URI** and requested **scopes**), then:

1. **Authorize** — send the user to consent:
   ```
   https://oauth.onshape.com/oauth/authorize
     ?response_type=code
     &client_id=<client_id>
     &redirect_uri=<registered redirect URI>
     &scope=OAuth2Read+OAuth2Write
   ```
   Common scopes: `OAuth2Read`, `OAuth2Write`, `OAuth2Delete`, `OAuth2ReadPII`.
   Onshape redirects back to your URI with `?code=<authorization code>`.

2. **Exchange** the code for tokens (`POST`, form-encoded):
   ```
   POST https://oauth.onshape.com/oauth/token
     grant_type=authorization_code
     code=<authorization code>
     client_id=<client_id>
     client_secret=<client_secret>
     redirect_uri=<same redirect URI>
   ```
   Returns `access_token`, `refresh_token`, `expires_in`, `token_type: Bearer`.

3. **Call** the API with `Authorization: Bearer <access_token>`.

4. **Refresh** when the access token expires — `POST /oauth/token` with
   `grant_type=refresh_token` + `refresh_token` + `client_id` + `client_secret`;
   you get a new access (and refresh) token. No HMAC, no `On-Nonce` for OAuth calls.

## Recipe

Prove the credentials work against the lightest authenticated endpoint,
`GET /api/v10/users/sessioninfo` (returns the calling user's id/name — non-mutating).

```bash
# Basic (simplest runnable form) — should print your user JSON, HTTP 200
curl -fsS -u "$ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY:$ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY" \
  https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10/users/sessioninfo

# HMAC-signed equivalent, reusing the project signer
python3 - <<'PY'
import os, requests
from examples.onshape.onshape_edit import hmac_headers
url = "https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10/users/sessioninfo"
h = hmac_headers("GET", url, os.environ["ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY"], os.environ["ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY"])
r = requests.get(url, headers=h); r.raise_for_status()
print("OK", r.json().get("name"))
PY
```

Creds-free proof that the signer + edit path are wired correctly (in-process mock,
no Onshape account):

```bash
python3 examples/onshape/onshape_edit.py --self-test
```

See @onshape/api for the worked feature edit that builds on this auth, and
@onshape/playwright for the cookie/2FA session path when the REST API can't express
an edit. The resource jds (@onshape/api and siblings) all depend on this file for
their auth detail.
